2026 Regular Session ENROLLED
SENATE RESOLUTION NO. 170
BY SENATOR TALBOT
A RESOLUTION
To urge and request the Department of Insurance and the Louisiana Department of Health
to conduct a joint comprehensive review and study of the implementation and
enforcement of Louisiana's biomarker testing coverage law and to report their
findings.
WHEREAS, Louisiana enacted legislation requiring health insurance coverage for
biomarker testing when supported by medical and scientific evidence and recognized clinical
practice guidelines; and
WHEREAS, biomarker testing plays a critical role in the diagnosis, treatment, and
management of cancer and other serious diseases by enabling personalized and
precision-based medical care; and
WHEREAS, delays between the initial physician request for biomarker testing and
the eventual administration of testing may negatively impact patient outcomes, delay
treatment decisions, and increase the risk of disease progression; and
WHEREAS, timely access to evidence-based biomarker testing is increasingly
recognized as a standard component of precision medicine and modern cancer care; and
WHEREAS, stakeholders, including patients, healthcare providers, laboratories, and
insurers, have raised concerns regarding access to biomarker testing, claims adjudication and
utilization management practices, use of Proprietary Laboratory Analyses (PLA) codes,
denial patterns, appeals processes, and delays in testing approval and administration; and
WHEREAS, the legislature has an interest in ensuring that the biomarker testing
coverage law is being implemented consistently, fairly, and in accordance with legislative
intent; and
WHEREAS, a comprehensive review of claims data and implementation practices
would assist the legislature in evaluating whether additional statutory or regulatory action
is necessary to ensure patient access to medically appropriate biomarker testing.
THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the Senate of the Legislature of Louisiana
