does hereby urge and request the Department of Insurance and the Louisiana Department of
Health to conduct a joint comprehensive review and study of the implementation and
enforcement of Louisiana's biomarker testing coverage law from January 1, 2024, through
the present.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that a written report of findings and
recommendations shall be submitted to the Senate and House committees on insurance and
the Senate and House committees on health and welfare no later than February 1, 2027.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the report shall include but not be limited to the
following:
(1) The number of biomarker testing claims submitted to health insurers and
managed care organizations operating in Louisiana.
(2) The number of claims approved, denied, partially denied, or otherwise not paid
in full.
(3) The reasons for denial or adverse benefit determinations, including prior
authorization requirements, medical necessity determinations, coding issues, network
limitations, or other administrative grounds.
(4) The average length of time between the initial request for biomarker testing by
a healthcare provider and the administration or completion of the test.
(5) The number and outcomes of appeals, reconsiderations, grievances, or external
reviews related to biomarker testing claims.
(6) A review of all adjudication and utilization management practices associated with
biomarker testing claims, including timelines for review and payment.
(7) The utilization and reimbursement of Proprietary Laboratory Analyses (PLA)
codes and any other billing codes commonly associated with biomarker testing.
(8) Aggregate approval, denial, and appeal data categorized by insurer, managed care
organization, and biomarker testing category to the extent permitted by law.
(9) Identification of any barriers to patient access to biomarker testing services,
including administrative, reimbursement, network-related, or timing-related barriers.
(10) Recommendations for legislative, regulatory, or administrative changes
necessary to improve compliance, transparency, and patient access.
